	(text_box "\nThis system is designed to power and control a ride-on vehicle for children with motor disabilities. The system can be powered from either a 24V or 12V lead-acid or LiFePO_{4} battery. A digital kill switch (K101) is used to power the vehicle on/off. \n\nThis system is intended to drive either two sets of two parallel motors for the front and rwear wheels respsectively. A 5th motor is used for steering, and steering feedback is provided by an analog sensor that measures the angle of the steering mechanism. \n\nThe system also can create audio outputs using an onboard DAC and 20W power amplifier. \n\nTo control the vehicle, this syustem offers a standardized control interface that utilizes the RJ45 connector. PWM signals are used to indicate steering and throttle. In addition, an RC module can be plugged into the board allowing remote operation. When the RC interface is active, the hardwired control system is locked out allowing the parent to override the child. \n\nThe board also includes interfaces for a UI device (M5stack dial) and action challenges. \n\n"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 25.4 101.6 0)
		(size 114.3 38.1)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
			(width 0)
			(type solid)
		)
		(fill
			(type none)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "2e18d782-122e-4d3b-a3d0-ce0dac75b57e")
	)
	(text_box "J102 pin 3 is normally shorted to GND. If charger is inserted, pin 3 goes Hi-Z, which disables the relay."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 29.21 80.01 0)
		(size 40.64 8.0376)
		(margins 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525 0.9525)
		(stroke
